################################################################################
################################################################################
	README for eval_training.py
################################################################################
################################################################################

An evaluation trainer!

Basic usage is as follows.

      eval_training.py --file <pgn file> --game <game> --move <move>

A chessboard of the given game (from the given file of pgns) at the
given move, will be shown.  Come up with an evaluation.  Close the
window, or press any key, to see what stockfish thinks!

################
## Some Notes ##
################

# Counting Games #
##################

For large pgn files, it can take some time to count the number of
games.  So, instead of counting the games in the input file, just fail
if the requested game is not available.

As an example, the LumbrasGigaBase.pgn file
[https://sourceforge.net/projects/lumbrasgigabase/files/], or at least
the one I have, has 13207715 games.  Counting this with a simple shell
command

   cat <the pgn file> | egrep '^\[Event\W' | wc -l

takes almost 3 minutes on my system.  So, there is no attempt to count games.

The move is treated the same way.  The command will fail if the
specified game does not have enough moves.
